      <main>
        <section class="introduction">
            <p>
                Cover and cook on dum/steam for a short time  to infuse  the flavour spicies and herbs. Tada! Your best restauarant style  Chicken Biriyani is ready
            </p>
        </section><br>
        <section class="ingredients">
            <h2>Ingredients</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>4 skinless chicken breasts, cut into large chunks.</li>
                <li>300g basmati rice.</li>
                <li>25g butter.</li>
                <li>1 large onion, finely sliced.</li>
                <li>1 bay leaf.</li>
                <li>3 cardamom pods.</li>
                <li>small cinnamon stick.</li>
                <li>1 tsp turmeric.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="process">
            <h2>Making process</h2>
            <p>The traditional process of Chicken Biryani starts by marinating meat in yogurt along with spices and herbs. The raw/uncooked marinated meat is layered at the bottom of a wide pot followed by another layer of par cooked basmati rice, herbs, saffron infused milk, fried onions and ghee or attar (edible essential oil).</p>
        </section>
        <section class="final">
            <h2>Final step</h2>
            <p>Dhum comes from the test used to show whether it is ready. The chef taps the vessel on the side and if it makes a 'dhum' sound the biryani is ready to be served.</p>
        </section>
